    <p class="gap-reason">
      <strong>Why the gap was so long:</strong> The Kubernetes VolumeAttachment object continued to report <code>attached: true</code> throughout the entire incident — the CSI driver has no mechanism to inspect EXT4 journal state. The disk was physically reattached by Azure at 22:34:55 (as /dev/sdh) within 6 minutes of the failure, but the kubelet did not re-mount it onto the existing Pod volume path. The dead /dev/sdg mount point silently returned EIO for all writes. The Neo4j <code>neo4j.RaftLogPr</code> process was observed failing to read Raft log directories from 22:37, but no alert fired immediately. The only observable kernel signal during the silent period was the <code>htree_dirblock_to_tree error -5</code> repeating every ~15 seconds for nearly 18 hours, which is post-abort noise not correlated to any alert rule. Detection appears to have required either a Neo4j application-level Raft panic or a manual investigation that triggered the read-only remount at 16:24:44.
    </p>
  </section>

